5. THIRD-PARTY SOFTWARE
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The MIT License above covers RE-Toolkit's own source: the installer, the analyzer
driver, the library modules, the analysis stages, the Ghidra postscript, and the
documentation in this repository.

It does NOT cover the third-party tools that install-retoolkit.sh provisions or
that analyze-binaries.sh invokes. Those remain under their own licenses, held by
their own authors, and are neither redistributed nor relicensed by this project.
RE-Toolkit orchestrates them; it does not vendor them.

Tools are obtained at install time from their upstream distributors, whether a
Debian or Kali package, a vendor release artifact, a container image, or a
source build. No warranty is offered as to the provenance, integrity, safety,
licensing, or behavior of any such artifact.

Review the license of any tool before redistributing it or incorporating its
output into a deliverable. Several carry terms materially different from MIT,
including copyleft terms that attach obligations to derived work, and terms that
restrict commercial or governmental use.

Rule sets are likewise separately licensed. The capability and signature rules
cloned during installation are the property of their respective projects and
carry their own terms.

Determining and satisfying your obligations under those licenses is your
responsibility.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. DUAL-USE NOTICE AND AUTHORIZED USE
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

RE-Toolkit is dual-use software. It installs and orchestrates tooling capable of
analyzing, deobfuscating, and reverse engineering software, including software
you did not author. When explicitly enabled, it executes untrusted binaries.

It is intended for defensive security work: malware analysis, incident response,
vulnerability research, software assurance, and assessment of systems you own or
are authorized to assess.

Reverse engineering may be restricted by license terms, by contract, or by law
in your jurisdiction. Export, re-export, or transfer of security tooling may be
subject to control. Determining what you are permitted to analyze, possess, and
transfer is your responsibility, not this project's.

Do not use RE-Toolkit against binaries, systems, networks, or services you lack
documented authorization to examine.

Nothing in the MIT grant above should be read as permission to conduct
unauthorized access, evade defensive controls, infringe intellectual property,
or violate applicable law. The grant is a copyright license only. It conveys no
authorization, consent, or right of access with respect to any third party's
software, systems, or data.
